    Level-1 Main Claim: {"claim": "Excluding entire food groups can be dangerous, and animal products provide vital nutrients.", "argument": ["Personal experience shows improved health after incorporating animal products.", "Weston Price's research supports the importance of traditional diets rich in animal products.", "Studies link vegetarianism and veganism to increased risks of mental disorders and nutrient deficiencies.", "Vital nutrients like cholesterol, B12, vitamin D, and zinc are more bioavailable in animal products.", "Supplementation cannot fully replicate the complex synergy of nutrients in whole foods.", "Focusing solely on studies linking meat consumption to negative outcomes ignores the biochemical link between nutrient deficiencies in vegetarian diets and mental health issues.", "Meta-analyses show significant vitamin B12 deficiency in vegetarians and vegans.", "Vitamin B12 deficiency demonstrates real-world health consequences of these diets.", "Healthy traditional diets across populations included animal foods.", "This includes diets of vulnerable populations.", "Animal products are crucial for nutrition.", "Individual nutritional needs vary across lifespans.", "Rejecting meat ignores individual variability.", "The motion goes against traditional diets.", "Traditional diets are not validated by modern science."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Plant-based diets are linked to improved health outcomes, including reduced risk of cancer and improved mental health.", "argument": ["The China Study shows a correlation between animal product consumption and increased health problems, including cancer.", "Randomized trials with 300 participants on plant-based diets demonstrated improvements in depression and anxiety levels.", "Switching to a plant-based diet reduces the risks of obesity.", "Switching to a plant-based diet reduces the risks of heart disease.", "Switching to a plant-based diet reduces the risks of cancer."]}
            Level-3 Your Rebuttal: {"claim": "Observational studies don't demonstrate causality between meat consumption and negative health outcomes.", "argument": ["Veganism arguments rely on observational studies.", "Observational studies cannot prove causation between meat consumption and negative health outcomes."]}
            Level-3 Your Rebuttal: {"claim": "Nutrient deficiencies common in vegetarian diets have a biochemical link to mental health issues.", "argument": ["Focusing solely on studies linking meat consumption to negative outcomes ignores the biochemical link between nutrient deficiencies in vegetarian diets and mental health issues."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "The argument that meat is necessary for B12 is a misconception, as B12 is produced by bacteria and supplementation is widely recommended regardless of diet.", "argument": ["B12 is produced by bacteria, not animals.", "Supplementation is recommended for everyone over 50, regardless of diet.", "Providing meat to B12-deficient individuals doesn't resolve the deficiency."]}
            Level-3 Your Rebuttal: {"claim": "Veganism leads to vitamin B12 deficiency.", "argument": ["Meta-analyses show significant vitamin B12 deficiency in vegetarians and vegans.", "Vitamin B12 deficiency demonstrates real-world health consequences of these diets."]}
